{{Portal|Catholicism}} 
'''Thomas Penswick''' (1772<U+2013>1836) was an [[English people|English]] [[Catholic Church|Roman Catholic bishop]] who served as the [[Vicar Apostolic of the Northern District (England)|Vicar Apostolic of the Northern District]] from 1831 to 1836.<ref name=bpens>{{Catholic-hierarchy|bishop|bpens|Bishop Thomas Penswick|22 June 2011}}</ref>

Born in [[Ashton-in-Makerfield]], [[Lancashire]] on 7 March 1772, he was [[Holy Orders|ordained]] to the [[Priesthood (Catholic Church)|priesthood]] on 1 April 1797. He was appointed [[Coadjutor bishop|coadjutor]] to the [[Vicar Apostolic of the Northern District (England)|Vicar Apostolic of the Northern District]], Bishop [[Thomas Smith (vicar apostolic)|Thomas Smith]], on 13 January 1824. On the same day, Penswick was appointed [[Titular Bishop]] of ''Europus'', and [[Consecration|consecrated]] to the [[Episcopal polity|Episcopate]] by Bishop [[William Poynter]] on 29 June 1824. On the death of [[Thomas Smith (vicar apostolic)|Bishop Smith]] on 30 July 1831, Bishop Penswick automatically succeeded as Vicar Apostolic of the Northern District.<ref name=bpens/>

He died in office on 28 January 1836, aged 63.<ref name=bpens/>

